DO_MESSAGE


public ForwardDoParms DO_MESSAGE(java.lang.String messageCode,
                                 EnumMessageType messageType,
                                 java.lang.String messageComponentName,
                                 EnumLanguage messageLanguage)




Sets a GUI component or a function variable with a localized coded message.

 

 The message must be defined in the forward generalized tables system in the rule table number

 assigned to the function, for messages to be showed.

 It will be searched in the oder a GUI component with the input name compatible with a text value

 to show, like a JTextField, JLabel and so on and, otherwise a variable name to be set.

 The input language overrides the language specified by function declaration or assigned to the

 user at login time.
 

 If the function doesn't declare a GUI component or a variable with the input name, no action will be taken.

 

 Message types can be:
        WARNING 
        INFORMATION 
        DEBUG 
        ERROR_INPUT 
        ERROR_FATAL 
   
 The key of each messsage rule table element is made by the ordinal of EnumMessageType followed 

 by the message code.

 












Parameters:
messageCode - the message code
messageType - the message type as a EnumMessageType enumeration
messageComponentName - the name of a GUI component or function variable
messageLanguage - the message language as a EnumLanguage enumeration










DO_NOTHING


public ForwardDoParms DO_NOTHING()




Action dummy.

 

 No operation will be executed.

 It migth be useful to make not operative standard actions.

 






















DO_MESSAGE


public ForwardDoParms DO_MESSAGE(java.lang.String messageCode,
                                 EnumMessageType messageType,
                                 java.lang.String messageComponentName)




Sets a GUI component or a function variable with a localized coded message.

 

 The message must be defined in the forward generalized tables system in the rule table number

 assigned to the function, for messages to be showed.

 It will be searched in the oder a GUI component with the input name compatible with a text value

 to show, like a JTextField, JLabel and so on and, otherwise a variable name to be set.

 The message language is the language declared by function or assigned by means of user login procedure.

 

 If the function doesn't declare a GUI component or a variable with the input name, no action will be taken.

 

 Message types can be:
        WARNING 
        INFORMATION 
        DEBUG 
        ERROR_INPUT 
        ERROR_FATAL 
   
 The key of each messsage rule table element is made by the ordinal of EnumMessageType followed 

 by the message code.

 












Parameters:
messageCode - the message code
messageType - the message type as a EnumMessageType enumeration
messageComponentName - the name of a GUI component or function variable










DO_LDV_RUN


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_RUN(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                 int limitRows)




Creates, validate and execute a logical data view

 

 It will be verified the existence of the input logical data view name 

 as a class and a new object will be obtained.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view to execute
limitRows - the max number of rows to get

                                     int limitRows)

 The logical data view is allowed to return a maximum number of rows as specified by input parameters.

 The dynamically built sql query will code the standard sql LIMIT parameters to limit the

 number of rows tro get.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 no action will be taken.

DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_GUI


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_GUI(java.lang.String ldvClassName)




Set logical data view root FOR_ANY() from GUI controls values

 

 This action must be used to set primary key values of the root FOR_ANY()

 of a logical data view, that can return one row or a set of rows, when some 

 FOR_EACH() declarations are following too.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or a FOR_ANY() is not the first declaration, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name










DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_VAR


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_VAR(java.lang.String ldvClassName)




Set logical data view root FOR_ANY() from variable values

 

 This action must be used to set primary key values of the root FOR_ANY()

 of a logical data view, that can return one row or a set of rows, when some 

 FOR_EACH() declarations are following too.

 Key values will be set using only variables with the same name.

 Setting using the current value of GUI controls, must be done with the action

 LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_GUI
 

 Actions DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_GUI and DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_ROOT_FROM_VAR

 allow you make keys setting automatic and dependent of what coded at function declaration time

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or a FOR_ANY() is not the first declaration, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name

public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_FIELDS_KEY_FROM_GUI(java.lang.String ldvClassName)




Set logical data view keys from GUI controls values

 

 This action must be used to set primary key values of all specified entities

 of a logical data view, declared by a FOR_ANY(), FOR_EACH(), INSERT(), DELETE() or UPDATE().

 

 All entity columns exposed with the same name of a GUI control will be updated with 

 the current value.
 
 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or a FOR_ANY() is not the first declaration, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name

DO_LDV_SET_FIELD


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_FIELD(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                       java.lang.String columnName,
                                       java.lang.Object columnValue,
                                       java.lang.Object serviceParm)




Set a logical data view field value.

 

 A logical data view field is an entity column, a java name as defined in the entity bean class

 or an alias java name as coded by AS clause in the FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH() declarations.

 The logical data view manager, for each column, allocates an internal variable, automatically

 updated at row retrieving time. 
 

 This action allow you to update the column variable with an object value. 

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or the object value is not of the correct type, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name
columnName - the java name of the column or the java name overrided by the AS newName clause on FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH()
columnValue - the value object to be assigned to the columName
serviceParm - as an object service parm to make unique the signature. null is a good value










DO_LDV_SET_FIELD


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_FIELD(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                       java.lang.String columnName,
                                       java.lang.String functionVarName)




Set a logical data view field value.

 

 A logical data view field is an entity column, a java name as defined in the entity bean class

 or an alias java name as coded by AS clause in the FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH() declarations.

 The logical data view manager, for each column, allocates an internal variable, automatically

 updated at row retrieving time. 
 

 This action allow you to update the column variable with an object value from a function declared variable by VAR()

 or from a GUI defined control with the same name and of a compatible type.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or the variable is not defined or it's type is not of the correct type, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name
columnName - the java name of the column or the java name overrided by the AS newName clause on FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH()
functionVarName - the variable name, in the application runtime system, to use as input to update the columName value or
 the name of a GUI control of compatible type.










DO_LDV_SET_VAR


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_VAR(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                     java.lang.String ldvVarName,
                                     java.lang.Object newVarValue,
                                     java.lang.Object serviceParm)




Set a logical data view variable value.

 

 A logical data view variable is a variable declared by a VAR() declaration.

 Variables declared in this way are mainly used to hold values, set externally by application,

 to be solved runtime at the creation of the sql query time.

 A VAR() declared variable is managed like an host variable of Sql language and it's inserted

 in the where condition in the same mode: with a : (semicolon) character to start the variable name.

 

 This action allow you to update this variable with an object value. 

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or the object value is not of the correct type, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name
ldvVarName - the java name of the column or the java name overrided by the AS newName clause on FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH()
newVarValue - the value object to be assigned to the ldvVarName
serviceParm - as an object service parm to make unique the signature. null is a good value










DO_LDV_SET_VAR


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_VAR(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                     java.lang.String ldvVarName,
                                     java.lang.String functionVarName)




Set a logical data view variable value.

 

 A logical data view variable is a variable declared by a VAR() declaration.

 Variables declared in this way are mainly used to hold values, set externally by application,

 to be solved runtime at the creation of the sql query time.

 A VAR() declared variable is managed like an host variable of Sql language and it's inserted

 in the where condition in the same mode: with a : (semicolon) character to start the variable name.

 

 This action allow you to update this variable with the contents of a variable declared and managed by function 

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 or the function variable is not of the correct type, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name
ldvVarName - the java name of the column or the java name overrided by the AS newName clause on FOR_ANY() or FOR_EACH()
functionVarName - the name of a function variable to be assigned to the ldvVarName

DO_LDV_SET_SQL_WHERE


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_SET_SQL_WHERE(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                           int entityIndex,
                                           java.lang.String whereSql,
                                           java.lang.Object dummy)




Set a supplementary sql where condition of a FOR_ANY/EACH declarative in a logical data view

 

 The logical data view may contain several access declaratives, and 

 a complex sql select, with all joins required, will be generated.

 Thereby normally nothing more it's necessary.

 When the application needs specific where conditions related to the access of an

 entity, depending on the currente status execution, can declare this action 

 to dynamically set the condition runtime.

 

 The sql where string must be a valid sql where condition with column names specified

 as the java bean name and not as the sql column name.

 

 If the logical data view has been not previously loaded or the declaration index is wrong, 

 no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name
entityIndex - the index 0-based of the declaration in the logical data view
whereSql - the sql where condition
dummy - as a dummy parameter only to make this method unique

 If the logical data view has been not previously loaded or the declaration index is wrong, 

 or the variable is not declared by function, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:

varName - the string function variable with the sql where condition

                                          EnumLanguage ldvLanguage)




Set the logical data view language for rule tables.

 

 This action is valid only when the logical data view does access to rule tables too. 

 In this case the where condition of the automatic sql statement created, will contains

 the constaint for the language specified.
 

 Your'e noticed that when there are not rows in the generalized Forward tables system

 for the input rule table specified, no rows at all will be returned to the application.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:

DO_LDV_UPDATE


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_UPDATE(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                    java.lang.String entityNameAs,
                                    java.lang.String idOperation,
                                    java.lang.String... ldvColsToExclude)




Update the database with the current logical data view row data.

 

 All entities declared by logical data view will be updated in CRUD modality, to say a row

 for each entity accessed, by the own primary key.

 

 Primary keys of all entities currently accessed by the logical data view are holded

 as variables by the logical data view.

 

 If the logical data view is not defined, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name to validate
entityNameAs - the entity name internal reference to update
idOperation - as an optional string identifier to be used as reference in ON_CONDITION() declarations
ldvColsToExclude - the columns list to exclude from the update  They are java column name defined by the entity bean.

 No column can be specified as a null value.










DO_LDV_INSERT


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_INSERT(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                    java.lang.String entityNameAs,
                                    java.lang.String idOperation,
                                    java.lang.String... ldvColsToExclude)




Insert the entity in the database with the current logical data view values, as a CRUD operation.

 

 The logical data view must declare an INSERT() of the input entity.

 

 The columns value is holded by logical data view and can be updated by means of

 the logical data view set methods.

 

 If the logical data view is not defined, or the entityName is not declared, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name to validate
entityNameAs - the entity name internal reference to be inserted
idOperation - as an optional string identifier to be used as reference in ON_CONDITION() declarations
ldvColsToExclude - the columns list to exclude from the update  They are java column name defined by the entity bean.

 No column can be specified.










DO_LDV_DELETE


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_DELETE(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                    java.lang.String entityNameAs,
                                    java.lang.String... idOperation)




Insert the entity in the database with the current logical data view values, as a CRUD operation.

 

 The logical data view must declare an DELETE() of the input entity

 

 The primary key columns value is holded by logical data view and can be updated by means of

 the logical data view set methods.

 

 If the logical data view is not defined, or the entityName is not declared, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view name to validate
entityNameAs - the entity name internal reference to be deleted
idOperation - as an optional string identifier to be used as reference in ON_CONDITION() declarations










DO_LDV_DB_SET_ACCESS_PARMS


public ForwardDoParms DO_LDV_DB_SET_ACCESS_PARMS(java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                                 int limitRows,
                                                 boolean ldvDbAutoCommit,
                                                 boolean ldvDbAutoConnection)




Set some parameters to access to  the database.

 

 The logical data view is allowed to return a maximum number of rows as specified by input parameters.

 The dynamically built sql query will code the standard sql LIMIT parameters to limit the

 number of rows tro get.

 

 If the logical data view is not declared, has been not created or validated,

 no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
ldvClassName - the logical data view to execute
ldvDbAutoCommit - as true for an automatic commit after updates
ldvDbAutoConnection - as true to let the logical data view manager to acquire and to release the connection automatically

DO_COMPONENT_MASK_EVENTS


public ForwardDoParms DO_COMPONENT_MASK_EVENTS(java.lang.String componentName,
                                               boolean componentEventsToMask,
                                               EnumForwardEvent... componentMaskedEvents)




Masks one or more events for a component.

 

 When an event is masked, no action declared by function will be taken when it occurs.

 

 It true for componentEventsToMask is specified, all events will be stored in the forward monitor

 structures and no action declared will be executed if any event occurs.

 If false is specified with no event list following, all events currently to be masked for the component 

 will be removed from the masked list events.

 

 When a specified event is not defined it will be discarded and no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the Swing component to make visible
componentEventsToMask - as true to fire events to be masked, false for normal behaviour
componentMaskedEvents - as an array of events to be masked or not

DO_COMBOBOX_GET_ORDINAL


public ForwardDoParms DO_COMBOBOX_GET_ORDINAL(java.lang.String componentName,
                                              java.lang.String ordinalVarNameReturned,
                                              java.lang.String ordinalVarNameValue,
                                              java.lang.String ordinalValue)




Gets the ordinal 0-based of the combobox item, in the specified input function declared variable.

 

 This action can be executed in any time for a populated combobox but it's mainly useful when

 executed under ON_COMBOBOX_SELECTED_ITEM event to retrieve the ordinal directly
 in a function variable declared by VAR().
 

 If the component is not declared or variables are not defined or of a wrong type, no action will be taken.

 if ordinalValue is null it will be considered the variable ordinalVarNameValue to get the item to locate.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the Swing comboBox name
ordinalVarNameReturned - the function declared variable that will contains the ordinal as an Integer object
ordinalVarNameValue - the function declared variable that will contains the string value to get the ordinal
ordinalValue - as a string value of which to get the ordinal. If an empty string it will be used the variable ordinalVarNameValue

 executed under ON_COMBOBOX_SELECTED_ITEM event to retrieve the ordinal directly

 If the component is not declared or variables are not defined or of a wrong type, no action will be taken.

DO_COMBOBOX_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND


public ForwardDoParms DO_COMBOBOX_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND(java.lang.String componentName,
                                                            java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                                            java.lang.String ldvColObjectBound)




Set the object bound for the item to be inserted in the combobox at populatiopn from db time.

 

 This action will be effective only when it's executed under ON_COMBOBOX_BEFORE_ADD_ELEMENT event

 The only effect of this action is to execute the setComboBoxBoundObject() method, 

 in the system object active runtime, with the new value, causing the new object to be bound to the

 item to add.

 The new object bound value will be the content of the specified column of the logical data view

 currently used to populate the combo box.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the swing component name
ldvClassName - the logical data view name currently used to populate the combobx
ldvColObjectBound - the column name to use as object bound










DO_COMBOBOX_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND


public ForwardDoParms DO_COMBOBOX_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND(java.lang.String componentName,
                                                            java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                                            java.lang.String ldvColObjectBound,
                                                            boolean objectBoundToInteger)




Set the object bound for the item to be inserted in the combobox at populatiopn time from db.

 

 This action will be effective only when it's executed under ON_COMBOBOX_BEFORE_ADD_ELEMENT event

 The only effect of this action is to execute the setComboBoxBoundObject() method, 

 in the system object active runtime, with the new value, causing the new object to be bound to the item to add.

 The new object bound value will be the content of the specified column of the logical data view

 currently used to populate the combo box.

 

 When the column bound is string defined and contains only numeric string values, as for all forward rule tables,

 may be necessary store the bound value directly as an Integer object.

 To  do so, it needs to code true in the objectBoundToInteger parameter.
 












Parameters:
componentName - the swing component name
ldvClassName - the logical data view name currently used to populate the combobx
ldvColObjectBound - the column name to use as object bound
objectBoundToInteger - as a boolean value to convert the object bound from String to integer.

                                          int listItemIndex)




Update the required item from a list

 

 Any item can be bound with an application dependent object, like a database key,

 a text or even a structured object.

 This bound object, if declared, will be deleted just only due the item deleting or the clear of list.

 In p constructor no bound object it's declared and its value will be not set.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the Swing list name
listItemText - the text item value
listItemIndex - the index of item to update

DO_TABLE_POPULATE_FROM_DB


public ForwardDoParms DO_TABLE_POPULATE_FROM_DB(java.lang.String componentName,
                                                java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                                java.lang.String[] tableJavaFieldsBound,
                                                java.lang.String[] tableLdvColumnsBound)




Populates the table by the execution of the logical data view

 

 The logical data view to be used will be that declared by DATA_SOURCE() at function declaration level.

 The logical data view has been declared to expose a set o columns with the java name coded in the bean entity class,

 eventually renamed by means of the AS clause at logical data view declaration level.

 

 By default, all swing controls or variables declared by VAR(), will be updated with the content of current table row,

 for all columns with the same name.

 

 First, input java fields and columns to bind, are used to populate the row, then only columns name exposed by logical

 data view are used.

 When name or column type doesn't match with a function variable or a swing component name, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the Swing comboBox name
ldvClassName - the logical data view class name
tableJavaFieldsBound - as a String array with names of swing controls or declared variables
tableLdvColumnsBound - as a String array with names of column names exposed by logical data view










DO_TABLE_POPULATE_FROM_DB


public ForwardDoParms DO_TABLE_POPULATE_FROM_DB(java.lang.String componentName,
                                                java.lang.String ldvClassName)




Populates the table by the execution of the logical data view

 

 The logical data view to be used will be that declared by DATA_SOURCE() at function declaration level.

 The logical data view has been declared to expose a set o columns with the java name coded in the bean entity class,

 eventually renamed by means of the AS clause at logical data view declaration level.

 

 All swing controls or variables declared by VAR(), will be updated with the content of current table row,

 for all columns with the same name.

 When name or column type doesn't match with a function variable or a swing component name, no action will be taken.

 












Parameters:
componentName - the Swing comboBox name
ldvClassName - the logical data view class name

Marks the current row to be used to populate the table as to be discarded

 The only effect of this action is to execute the setTableRowToDiscard(true) method,
 in the system object active runtime.

DO_TABLE_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND


public ForwardDoParms DO_TABLE_POPULATE_SET_OBJECT_BOUND(java.lang.String componentName,
                                                         java.lang.String ldvClassName,
                                                         java.lang.String ldvColObjectBound)




Set the object bound for the row to be inserted in the table at populatiopn time from db.

 

 This action will be effective only when it's executed under ON_TABLE_BEFORE_ADD_ROW event

 The only effect of this action is to execute the setTableBoundObject() method, 

 in the system object active runtime, with the new value, causing the new object to be bound to the row to add.

 The new object bound value will be the content of the specified column of the logical data view

 currently used to populate the table.

 

 This action, executed under the table populating process, should be used when the object bound is an 

 elementary variable, identified by a column of the logical data view used to populate the table.

 

 When data to bound are more then one logical data view column or they are a complex structure, the application

 must code a reusable method to store the desired object bound.
 
 So, under ON_TABLE_BEFORE_ADD_ROW event, a  DO_EXEC_METHOD() must be declared.

 

 Here is an example to set as objecy bound a String array with three column values:
        ON_EVENT(EnumForwardEvent.ON_TABLE_BEFORE_ADD_ROW, "tb_metricsViolations", DO_EXEC_METHOD("metricsViolationsSetObjectBound"));  
           --
           --
           --
            public int metricsViolationsSetObjectBound(ForwardSystem s, ForwardFunction f) {
                ForwardLogicalDataView ldv = null;
                String[] ar_objBound = null;

                ldv = (ForwardLogicalDataView) s.getLdvObject();
                ar_objBound = new String[3];
                ar_objBound[0] = ldv.getValueString("originViolation");
                ar_objBound[1] = ldv.getValueString("originViolationRows");
                ar_objBound[2] = ldv.getValueString("originViolationRowsCopy");
                s.setTableBoundObject(ar_objBound);
                return 0;
            }
 

 The row object bound can then retreived at the table row selection.
 Here is an example to get the object bound previously stored to populate, by manual code, another table (tb_metricsViolationsOrigin):
                     
 ON_EVENT(EnumForwardEvent.ON_TABLE_ROWS_SELECTED, "tb_metricsViolations",  DO_TABLE_DELETE_ALL_ROWS("tb_metricsViolationsOrigin")
                                                                                            , DO_EXEC_METHOD("metricsViolationsOriginPopulate"))

            public int metricsViolationsOriginPopulate(ForwardSystem s, ForwardFunction f) {

                ForwardTableModel tableModelViolationsOrigin = null;
                String[] ar_originViolation = null;
                String[] ar_originViolationRows = null;
                String[] ar_originViolationRowsCopy = null;
                String[] ar_objBound = null;
                String originViolation = "";                                                     
                String originViolationRows = "";                                                 
                String originViolationRowsCopy = "";                             
                String instr = "";
                String row = "";
                String rowCopy = "";

                ar_objBound = (String[]) s.getTableBoundObject();
                originViolation = ar_objBound[0];
                originViolationRows = ar_objBound[1];
                originViolationRowsCopy = ar_objBound[2];

                ar_originViolation = originViolation.split(" ");
                ar_originViolationRows = originViolationRows.split(" ");
                ar_originViolationRowsCopy = originViolationRowsCopy.split(" ");

                if (ar_objBound[2].equals("null")) {
                        ar_originViolationRowsCopy = new String[ar_originViolationRows.length];
                        for (int i = 0; i < ar_originViolationRowsCopy.length; i++) {
                                ar_originViolationRowsCopy[i] = "";
                                }
                        }

                if (originViolation.equals("")) {
                        ar_originViolation = new String[ar_originViolationRows.length];
                        for (int i = 0; i < ar_originViolation.length; i++) {
                                ar_originViolation[i] = "";
                                }
                        }

                // Modello tabella
                tableModelViolationsOrigin = getPanelComponent("tb_metricsViolationsOrigin").getTableModel();

                // Scan  
                for (int i = 1; i < ar_originViolation.length; i++) {
                        instr = ar_originViolation[i];
                        row = ar_originViolationRows[i];
                        rowCopy = ar_originViolationRowsCopy[i];
                        al_rowToAppend = new ArrayList
